<br>
In particular, I have never receieved any acknowledgement of receipt, let alone action, on any <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /bug</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> report I have ever filed.  In contrast, when I <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /petition</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, I usually get a response back from a guide or GM.  If escalated to their website, I get a response back by e-mail: first, an acknowledgement of receipt, and later, an explanation of their action or inaction, including supporting server side log files.<br>
<br>
In contrast, when I <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /bug</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, I might as well be writing to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /dev/null</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for all the response it produces.<br>
<br>
This is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>not</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> acceptable.  At minimum, there needs to be some automated acknowledgement of receipt of the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /bug</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and ideally, a way to track and verify responses.<br>
<br>
A couple monthes back, I apologized to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Absor</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for promoting the idea that the most efficient way to get a bug fix was to first, find a way to exploit it, and second, to publicize that exploit in order to force <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s hand.  Although this is an extremely disrespectful way to treat the development staff, the fact remains: publicizing abuses generates a response, both an acknowledgement by <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> staff, and action by the programming staff.<br>
<br>
In contrast, there appears to be no visible benefit to filing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /bug</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> reports.<br>
<br>
Thus I am once again reduced to dealing in a public forum that which should be a regular business process of direct communication between the customer and the provider.<br>
<br>
Here are the list of problems involving horses that have been <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /bug</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->ged, many repeatedly, but which have not been acknowledged, let alone resolved.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Corpse dragging:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Dragging a corpse while riding a horse will quickly cause the corpse to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;fall beneath the earth.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Either disable corpse dragging from horseback, or else fix it.  <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>This bug is trivially reproduced.</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Horse invisibility:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> When one goes invisible while mounted, although the horse <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>appears</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> invisible, it is not.  It is also green to a level 60.  When travelling <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;invisible&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> on horseback, the low level horse aggro's creatures around it, which causes them to attack the horse.  However, anything which attempts to target the horse is automatically retargetted to the rider, so the aggro'ed mob attacks the rider instead, breaking invisibility.  <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>This bug is trivially reproduced.</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Horse levitation:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Levitation only works when the buff is cast while one is mounted.  Mounting while levitated, or zoning while mounted and levitated retains the levitation buff, but has no actual effect.  The net result is that one must constantly recast levitation while mounted, refreshing whenever zoning or re-mounting.  <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>This bug is trivially reproduced.</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Old horse distance bugs:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  When mounted, often one gets a distance bug with another player, most commonly when the terrain is not completely flat.  From then on, you cannot trade with that character, nor can that character cast spells on you, as they get an <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;out of range&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> message.  Once one has the distance bug with another character, dismounting or having either character zone or camp usually fixes it, but the bug may be reacquired shortly.  This bug can be fatal when the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;distant&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> character is the healer.  The rider can still cast on the bugged character, but cannot trade or be the recipient of targetted ranged spells by them.  You can be touching the other character, and they still get the out of range message.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> New horse distance bugs:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Ever since the new <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Line of Sight</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> spell targetting changes, an entirely new and extremely inconvenient distance bug has emerged.  Often, with no obvious pattern, nearby NPC targets, including pets and mobs, are out of range for individual spell casts.  The out of range message occurs sometimes before, and sometimes after the spell is cast.  Repeating the spell cast often but not always allows the spell to be cast, i.e., it is now in range again, even though neither party has moved.  One can move <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>closer</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, and the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;out of range&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> message still occurs.  Alternately, one can move <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>farther away</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> and successfully cast the spell.  You can be touching the mob or pet, close enough to get all emote, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /say</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and spell effect messages, and still get the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;out of range&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> message.  Repeatedly recasting the spell is the quickest work around, but with long casts this is not an acceptable solution.<br>
<br>
The main difference between the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;old&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;new&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> horse distance bugs is that the old bug affects other PCs casting on you, whereas the new bug affects your casts on NPCs.  Given the mage's dependency on casting spells, this bug can be fatal.<br>
<br>
While I am at it, here is one bug that is not horse related:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Click action tied to single button:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Sometimes while using the new UI, it breaks and acts like this.  No matter what active part of the screen you click on, it appears visually as if the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Pet Info -&gt; Go Away</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> button is being depressed, but no action is taken.  That is, if you try to click the mouse to cast a spell, press a button, remove a buff, target an enemy, press a hot key, close a window, access inventory, right click an item, or give another text window focus <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (such as /bug to report this)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, the only thing the UI does is display the appearance of the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Pet Info -&gt; Go Away</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> button and nothing else happens.  While this is happening, only keyboard commands works, including / commands, ALT-Spell casts, and pressing user defined hot-keys.  Camping out restores the user interface.  It is not common.  I use no mods, and will use no mods until the new UI is demonstrably stable.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> CONCLUSIONS:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
Until these bugs are addressed, casters should think twice before purchasing a horse, as they may find themselves unable to cast spells on NPCs, and unable to be buffed or healed by others.<br>
<br>
It is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>inexcusable</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /bug</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> generates no visible response from <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  At minimum, some form of acknowledgement of receipt of a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> /bug</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> must be implemented, and a means for customers to track the progress of bugs should be undertaken in the near future.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Sage ArchMage Razamatazz Pizzazz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Abuser of EZCodes</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
