<br>
All that listing open bugs would do is to assure you that something is or is not getting fixed.  If not, then you could apply more pressure to VI to get it fixed.<br>
<br>
They know this.  Dev organizations *hate* publically viewable lists of bugs.  It makes them look like they're not doing anything because they remain static for so long.  In reality, a triage is done when bugs are reported, and the bug is classified and prioritized.<br>
<br>
Critical bugs are fixed.  Bugs that focus around functionality currently being worked on are fixed.  Difficult bugs that if you fixed would destabilize the product are put on the back burner.  Easy bugs that are not easily reproducible (usually means the once or twice someone tries) are lowered in priority.<br>
<br>
The problem is that most dev organizations never go back and reprioritize bugs, unless pushed by some outside force.  That means that you get a stack of old bugs that nobody is making any concerted effort to fix.<br>
<br>
Putting in a way of listing those bugs would allow you, the customer, a way of complaining with more facts to back you up.  It would also mean pushing into the light that entire stack of old, unworked on and never planned to be worked on, bugs.  It would mean having to explain over and over again why they haven't fixed something in 3 years or more.<br>
<br>
It would air their dirty laundry where everyone could see.<br>
<br>
Now, if you had a Customer Service department that was actually focused on making the product better as opposed to being a remedial aid to product bugs, you might see this happen.  It takes an anormous amount of effort and political capital in a company, but I've seen CS departments pull something like this off.<br>
<br>
I've done it in the past.  It's hard.  Sometimes it takes *years* to get a bug list out to customers.<br>
<br>
But, VI's CS department is a joke.  It's powerless to make change in the company.  It's sole purpose is to shield the developers from nasty complaints, and it doesn't even do that very well.  <br>
<br>
In addition, we've gone through at least one, and quite possibly two, sets of developers since the original crew.  They are not all that interested in fixing other peoples bugs.  They'd much rather work on new content and new functionality.  That's true of all developers, and especially true of developers brought onto an existing product.<br>
<br>
Now, that doesn't make them bad people.  It makes them human, is all.  Nobody likes to clean up someone else's mess.<br>
<br>
So, Absor's comments aside, shaming them into action is still the best way of making them fix a bug.  Make an executive embarrassed somehow, and you'll get action.  Otherwise, they have no incentive to go back and re-prioritize a bug to the top of the list.<br>
<br>
My 2cp worth.  Backed up by 19 years experience in the software industry, dealing with exactly these kinds of problems.<br>
